## 5. MikroTik hAP² — initial setup

Use **Winbox** ([mikrotik.com/download](https://mikrotik.com/download)) or SSH. Default IP is often `192.168.88.1` / user `admin` (no password on first boot — set one immediately).

### 5.1 Reset (optional, factory-fresh router)

In Winbox: **System → Reset Configuration** → check **No Default Configuration** if you want a clean slate, then reset. Reconnect at `192.168.88.1`.

### 5.2 Identity and password

```routeros
/system identity set name=TesNet-HAP
/user set admin password="STRONG_ROUTER_PASSWORD"
```

### 5.3 Bridge + LAN ports + Wi‑Fi

Typical hAP² layout: **ether1 = WAN**, **ether2–ether5 + wlan = LAN bridge**.

```routeros
/interface bridge add name=bridge-lan
/interface bridge port add bridge=bridge-lan interface=ether2
/interface bridge port add bridge=bridge-lan interface=ether3
/interface bridge port add bridge=bridge-lan interface=ether4
/interface bridge port add bridge=bridge-lan interface=ether5
/interface bridge port add bridge=bridge-lan interface=wlan1

/ip address add address=192.168.88.1/24 interface=bridge-lan
```

Configure **WAN** (adjust for your ISP — DHCP example):

```routeros
/ip dhcp-client add interface=ether1 disabled=no
/ip firewall nat add chain=srcnat out-interface=ether1 action=masquerade
```

Wi‑Fi (2.4 GHz example — set SSID and WPA2 password):

```routeros
/interface wireless security-profiles add name=tesnet-wpa mode=dynamic-keys \
    authentication-types=wpa2-psk wpa2-pre-shared-key="WIFI_PASSPHRASE"

/interface wireless set wlan1 mode=ap-bridge ssid=TesNet-Student \
    security-profile=tesnet-wpa disabled=no
```

### 5.4 DHCP for hotspot clients

```routeros
/ip pool add name=hotspot-pool ranges=192.168.88.10-192.168.88.254
/ip dhcp-server add name=dhcp-hotspot interface=bridge-lan address-pool=hotspot-pool disabled=no
/ip dhcp-server network add address=192.168.88.0/24 gateway=192.168.88.1 \
    dns-server=192.168.88.1
/ip dns set allow-remote-requests=yes servers=8.8.8.8,1.1.1.1
```

### 5.5 Hotspot profile + server

Create profile (portal URL = your Laravel `APP_URL`):

```routeros
/ip hotspot profile add name=tesnet-profile \
    html-directory=hotspot \
    login-by=http-pap,cookie \
    http-cookie-lifetime=1d \
    use-radius=yes \
    ssl-certificate=none

/ip hotspot add name=tesnet-hotspot interface=bridge-lan address-pool=hotspot-pool \
    profile=tesnet-profile disabled=no
```

Upload a minimal **`login.html`** to the router’s `hotspot` folder (Winbox → **Files**) that sends users to Laravel:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta http-equiv="refresh" content="0;url=http://192.168.88.2/portal/login">
  <title>TesNet</title>
  <script>location.replace("http://192.168.88.2/portal/login");</script>
</head>
<body>
  <p>Redirecting to TesNet portal…</p>
  <p><a href="http://192.168.88.2/portal/login">Continue</a></p>
</body>
</html>
```

Use your Laravel `APP_URL` (LAN: `http://192.168.88.2`; production HTTPS: `https://portal.yourdomain.com`). See [`docs/PROBOOK_MIKROTIK_FULL_SETUP.md`](docs/PROBOOK_MIKROTIK_FULL_SETUP.md).

### 5.6 RADIUS on MikroTik (must match FreeRADIUS `clients.conf`)

```routeros
/radius add service=hotspot address=192.168.88.2 secret="CHANGE_ME_RADIUS_SECRET" timeout=3s
/ip hotspot profile set tesnet-profile use-radius=yes radius-accounting=yes
/ip hotspot set tesnet-hotspot radius=default
```

Accounting must be enabled so TesNet can track data usage in `radacct`.

### 5.7 Configure walled garden (allow Paystack, block free internet)

Unauthenticated clients must **only** reach your portal and Paystack. Everything else stays blocked until RADIUS accepts them after **Connect to Internet**.

Follow these steps **in order** on the hAP² (Winbox terminal or SSH).

#### Step 1 — Clear old / unsafe rules

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip print
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip remove [find]
/ip hotspot walled-garden print
/ip hotspot walled-garden remove [find]
```

Never leave rules like `0.0.0.0/0`, whole subnets, or “allow all HTTPS”.

#### Step 2 — Add the minimum allow list

Replace `portal.yourdomain.com` with the hostname from Laravel `APP_URL`.

**Portal on LAN only** (`192.168.88.2`, no public hostname):

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-address=192.168.88.2 action=accept comment="TesNet portal server"
```

**Portal via hostname** (HTTPS / production):

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=portal.yourdomain.com action=accept comment="TesNet portal"
```

**Paystack** (checkout before hotspot login):

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=paystack.com action=accept comment="Paystack"
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=*.paystack.com action=accept comment="Paystack subdomains"
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=checkout.paystack.com action=accept
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=standard.paystack.co action=accept
```

**Cloudflare Tunnel** (only if `APP_URL` uses it):

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip add dst-host=your-tunnel.cfargotunnel.com action=accept comment="CF tunnel"
```

Verify — you should see **only** 5–8 rows, nothing with `dst-address=0.0.0.0/0`:

```routeros
/ip hotspot walled-garden ip print
```

Do **not** add `8.8.8.8`, `1.1.1.1`, or `0.0.0.0/0` to the garden.

| Never add | Why |
|-----------|-----|
| `dst-address=0.0.0.0/0` | Full free internet before login |
| Allow all port 443 | Same leak |
| VPN/proxy hosts | Bypass hotspot |
| Hotspot trial user | Free access without payment |

#### Step 3 — Disable trial and local hotspot users

```routeros
/ip hotspot profile set tesnet-profile \
    trial-uptime=0s \
    trial-uptime-limit=0s \
    trial-user-profile="" \
    open-status-page=http-login \
    use-radius=yes \
    radius-accounting=yes

/ip hotspot user print
/ip hotspot user remove [find name!="admin"]
```

Students authenticate via **RADIUS only** (TesNet `radcheck`) — no `/ip hotspot user` entries in production.

#### Step 4 — Remove bypass bindings

Bypass bindings give full internet without login.

```routeros
/ip hotspot ip-binding print
/ip hotspot ip-binding remove [find type=bypassed]
```

Never set student phones to `type=bypassed`.

#### Step 5 — No firewall shortcut around hotspot

All Wi‑Fi clients must use the hotspot server:

```routeros
/ip hotspot print
/ip hotspot profile print
```

Check custom forward rules that leak traffic:

```routeros
/ip firewall filter print where chain=forward
```

Remove any rule that accepts `src-address=192.168.88.0/24` to WAN without hotspot authentication.

#### Step 6 — Lock router admin away from students

```routeros
/ip service set winbox address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
/ip service set api address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
/ip service set www address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
/ip service set ssh address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
/ip service disable telnet
/ip service disable ftp
```

Use your management IP if not the billing server — but **never** `192.168.88.0/24` for Winbox/API.

#### Step 7 — Test for leaks (required)

Phone on **TesNet-Student** Wi‑Fi, **do not** click Connect yet:

| Test | Must result |
|------|-------------|
| Portal login URL | Works |
| Paystack checkout | Works |
| `https://google.com` | **Blocked** |
| `https://youtube.com` | **Blocked** |

After payment, **before** Connect: `google.com` still **blocked**.

After **Connect to Internet**: browsing works (within plan).

If Google works before Connect, repeat Steps 1–6.

```routeros
/log print where topics~"hotspot"
/ip hotspot active print
```

### 5.8 How TesNet avoids a payment → free-internet loop

**§5.7** stops leaks on the router. TesNet adds a second layer in software:

```text
Paystack verified  →  plan in DB + RADIUS  →  still no hotspot session
Connect button     →  MikroTik /login       →  browsing allowed
```

Payment is verified server-side before fulfillment. `connectToWifi` blocks users with no active plan. Portal login ≠ hotspot login.

No extra router commands needed for this — configure **§5.7** correctly.

See [`docs/HOTSPOT.md`](docs/HOTSPOT.md).
### 5.9 Optional — MikroTik API (admin session disconnect)

In `.env` on the server:

```env
MIKROTIK_API_ENABLED=true
MIKROTIK_API_HOST=192.168.88.1
MIKROTIK_API_PORT=8728
MIKROTIK_API_USER=admin
MIKROTIK_API_PASSWORD=STRONG_ROUTER_PASSWORD
MIKROTIK_API_SSL=false
```

On MikroTik, restrict API access to the billing server only:

```routeros
/ip service set api address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
/ip service set winbox address=192.168.88.2/32 disabled=no
```

